Every time a button is pressed, I want to ensure that if a goroutine is already running and handling previous input, the new goroutine exits. I see two ways to do this. One is using a channel with one sized buffer or launching a always running goroutine and sending the button presses to it using a select to make it nonblocking.

Here is option one (work is the robot's work function):

``` go
var running = make(chan struct{}, 1)

func work() {
    gobot.On(button.Event("push"), func(data interface{}) {
        log.Print(data)
        select {
        case running <- struct{}{}:
        default:
            return
        }
        defer func() {
            <-running
        }()
        // work
    })
}
```

``` go
var push = make(chan struct{})

func work() {
    go realWork()
    gobot.On(button.Event("push"), func(data interface{}) {
        log.Print(data)
        select {
        case push <- struct{}{}:
        default:
            return
        }
    })
}

func realWork() {
    for {
        <-push
        // work
    }
}
```

Which would be better?

